<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / UK Company News: Holmes &amp; Marchant back in the black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Holmes &amp; Marchant, the marketing services group, returned to the black at
the pre-tax level in the six months to March 31.
Profits emerged at Pounds 299,000 (losses Pounds 715,000) on turnover some
Pounds 200,000 lower at Pounds 16.7m. Operating profits from continuing
businesses rose 27 per cent to Pounds 1.22m (Pounds 963,000) after
administrative expenses declined to Pounds 5.62m (Pounds 6.16m) following
rationalisation.
Lower interest rates meant a reduced charge of Pounds 451,000 (Pounds
511,000) and exceptional items, again relating to reorganisation and empty
property costs, fell to Pounds 471,000 (Pounds 1.05m).
Mr John Holmes, chairman, said that borrowings had shrunk by Pounds 500,000
to Pounds 8.5m since the year-end and that there was only 'minimal' deferred
consideration - a blight on the whole sector since the acquisitive 1980s -
still outstanding.
He said that although public relations and medical marketing were still
subdued, there were 'positive indications of increased activity' in design
and sales promotion.
Earnings were 1p (losses 2p).
</TEXT>
