<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / UK Company News: First quarter recovery at GA - Estimate of
net loss from the Bishopsgate bomb increased to Pounds 10m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL ACCIDENT yesterday provided further evidence of the turnround in the
general insurance market with better-than-expected first quarter figures.
The Perth-based composite insurer reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 41.9m
in the first three months of 1993, compared with a Pounds 29m loss in the
same period of 1992. The shares rose 18p to 591p.
A fall in worldwide underwriting losses of Pounds 54.5m to Pounds 80.5m, was
underpinned by a strong performance in the UK where GA was boosted by the
impact of higher premiums, milder weather and cuts in operating costs.
UK underwriting losses fell to Pounds 4m (Pounds 65m), in spite of a pay -
out of Pounds 3m after flooding in Scotland in January.
GA has revised its estimate of net losses from the Bishopsgate bomb in April
to Pounds 10m compared to earlier estimates of Pounds 7m. The loss will
affect second quarter figures.
Overall premium income rose to Pounds 1.02bn (Pounds 914.7m) for general
business and to Pounds 207m (Pounds 165.1m) for life business. In the UK the
book of household business was expanded with premium income rising to Pounds
71m (Pounds 47.3m), following the acquisition of a block of business from
the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester building society last October.
Investment income - after loan interest - increased to Pounds 115.6m (Pounds
102.7m). Losses from estate agency operations fell to Pounds 3.7m (Pounds
4.5m). Life profits amounted to Pounds 10.5m (Pounds 7.8m).
The company did not intend to follow the example of Commercial Union and
Royal Insurance by raising fresh capital through a rights issue in order to
take advantage of rising rates, said Mr Nelson Robertson, chief general
manager.
Mr Robertson said his company's capital base was adequate, its solvency
margin - the yardstick which measures net assets as a percentage of non-life
premium income - amounting to 46.1 per cent, compared to 41.5 per cent at
the end of 1992.
GA raised Pounds 250m in cumulative preference shares last year.
See Lex
</TEXT>
