<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Gencor moves to unbundle all non-mining units: Group seeks
greater focus - Talks start on Royal Dutch Shell metal interests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENCOR, South Africa's second largest mining house, yesterday announced that
it plans to unbundle its non-mining interests in a deal that will probably
halve the group's market capitalisation to about R8bn (Pounds 1.6bn) from
R16bn.
Gencor also disclosed that it is involved in talks with Royal Dutch Shell
for the acquisition of its main metal mining businesses. Discussions are at
an early stage, but if successful would see the creation of a world-scale
mining enterprise.
The effect of the Gencor unbundling, expected to be completed by August 31,
is that Gencor will relinquish control of its three industrial arms  - paper
and pulp company Sappi, consumer group Malbak and energy company Engen - as
well as investment arm Genbel. Gencor will emerge as purely a mining, metals
and mineral processing company, with interests in gold, platinum, coal,
ferro-alloys, stainless steel and aluminium.
Although Gencor said the move was motivated by the desire to unlock
shareholder wealth - it trades at a discount of about 19 per cent, or
R3.8bn, to net asset value - and improve focus for operations and investors,
Mr Brian Gilbertson, executive chairman, conceded there had been a political
angle to the deal. Unbundling is a policy much favoured by the African
National Congress.
The announcement was favourably received in the investment community. It
will also bring some of South Africa's unwieldly conglomerates into line
with trends towards more focused operations.
Mr Derek Keys, finance minister, and chairman of Gencor when the unbundling
issue was raised nearly three years ago, also endorsed the deal. 'I welcome
the announcement of the plan to unbundle in the belief that it will result
in five entrepreneurs,' he said.
The restructure will involve Gencor passing its shares in Sappi, Malhold,
Genbel and Engen to its own shareholders. Gencor Beherend, the controlling
pyramid, which has only a 54 per cent stake in Gencor, will pass its shares
in the underlying companies to shareholders (50 per cent Sanlam and 25 per
cent Rembrandt, the tobacco group) and be liquidated.
Mr Marinus Daling, chief executive of Sankorp, which controls Sanlam's
strategic investments, and the key driving force behind the unbundling, said
that Sankorp supported the unbundling 'because focus is extremely important
to us as investors'.
Gencor plans to supplement existing cash holdings of about R1.5bn by raising
a further R1.5bn by disposing of group shares and portfolio investments.
Thus, by the time of unbundling, Genmin will be about R1.5bn larger.
Lex, Page 20;
Editorial comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
