<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Directed by Richard Eyre, written by Ian McEwan and starring Harriet Walter,
is a pretty impressive combination so The Imitation Game (BBC 2 at 9pm)
demands attention. It was first broadcast in 1980 and is revived as part of
the tribute season to Richard Eyre, now director of the National Theatre.
Walter is a young girl, anxious to join the war effort in 1940, whose
enthusiasm evaporates when confronted by male condescension.
Newsreader Martyn Lewis's plea for more good news should be satisfied in
QED: Gallop to Freedom (BBC 1 at 9.30pm), which follows attempts to revive
the Przewalski horse. This was the horse of antiquity, immortalised in the
cave paintings at Lascaux.
Tight budgets do not allow much costume drama on screen, especially when it
involves the recreation of battles. So a welcome for Sharpe in which Sean
Bean buckles his swash as a lieutenant in Wellington's army in Spain during
the Peninsula War. In this episode (ITV at 8pm) he rallies his men to
recover the lost regimental colours and ideally to capture a French eagle.
</TEXT>
