<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Urban renewal policy attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORK of urban development corporations has proved expensive and has not
had much impact on inner-city communities, says a report published today.
The study, prepared for the Baring Foundation and the Joseph Rowntree
Charitable Trust, says the government has failed to give the corporations a
clear remit about their responsibilities to local communities, leaving each
corporation to decide for itself. The report singles out the corporations'
emphasis on property regeneration for criticism. The government, which funds
the corporations, should clarify their objectives, it adds.
The report says the government has been ambivalent about the corporations'
role in helping to create jobs.
It includes a mid-term analysis of the performance of the Tyne &amp; Wear and
Teesside development corporations, which it says have together spent more
than Pounds 300m in the past five years, becoming big operators in the
business of reconstruction.
But the report, by Durham University's department of sociology and social
policy, describes the performance of the two corporations in job creation as
disappointing.
It recommends that corporations should be less secretive and set up systems
to monitor community benefit. It predicts the government will conclude that
corporations turned out to be 'an expensive experiment with a high
cost-per-job and poorly targeted benefits'.
More than Bricks and Mortar? Department of Sociology and Social Policy,
University of Durham, Elvet Riverside, Durham DHI 3JT.
</TEXT>
