<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / E Midlands confident on sales outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURING output in the east Midlands remains sluggish, but business
confidence in the region is high.
These are the mixed findings of the latest regional business survey
conducted by Price Waterhouse, the accountants, and Nottingham Business
School, which is published today.
The survey, covering 973 companies, the vast majority of which employ fewer
than 200 people, notes that 66 per cent of companies across all sectors
predict an increase in sales over the next six months.
But the survey says 'manufacturing volumes show few signs of increasing with
only 27 per cent of businesses reporting that current utilisation of
capacity is above 90 per cent.' Six months ago, when the last survey was
published, the proportion was 29 per cent.
Economic recovery is signalled by a number of findings, however. For 39 per
cent of companies order books are fatter than in spring last year. Stock
turnover has started to speed up for 29 per cent of companies, compared with
24 per cent six months ago, and 39 per cent of businesses reported increased
profitability.
Yet companies expect the programme of pit closures in the Midlands to hold
back consumer spending and increase unemployment.
Reflecting the national experience, the speed of increase in the number of
unemployed people has slowed. Twenty-eight per cent of companies expect to
enlarge their workforce in the next half-year.
The balance in the labour market remains in favour of employers. More than
half the wage awards in the past six months have been less than 2.5 per
cent. Only 9 per cent of awards exceeded 5 per cent.
East Midlands Business Survey, Spring 1993. Price Waterhouse in association
with Nottingham Business School. Nottingham Business School, Nottingham
Trent University, NG1 4BU. Pounds 75.
</TEXT>
