<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / 'Green' project at Consett steel site
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS WERE unveiled yesterday for the Pounds 100m transformation of the
former Consett steelworks site in County Durham into environmentally
friendly parkland, comprising 1m sq ft of industrial and commercial
premises, houses and leisure amenities amid woodland and open space.
The 700-acre hilltop site has stood empty since the works closed in 1980,
costing Consett its final 3,600 steelmaking jobs and turning the town into a
symbol of the last manufacturing recession.
Yesterday, after years of preparation, Derwentside District Council
announced it had chosen Dysart Developments, developer of Newcastle's Pounds
140m Business Park, to undertake the seven-year scheme. The council hopes
Project Genesis will create 4,000 jobs and confirm Consett's new 'green'
identity.
Reclamation of the site cost Pounds 10m in government money. The council is
transferring ownership to a charitable trust, which will lease the land to
Dysart. The Pounds 100m project cost includes Pounds 13m in UK and European
Community funds with the rest coming from the private sector.
</TEXT>
