<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / MPs and OFT to attack CD prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MUSIC industry will today suffer the first of two expected attacks when
the Commons national heritage committee publishes a report criticising the
high price of compact discs.
The committee report, out this morning, is expected to be followed within a
few days by a recommendation from the Office of Fair Trading that the
industry's pricing policies be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Both the committee and the OFT are expected to concentrate on restrictions
on 'parallel imports'. The restrictions, set out in the Copyright, Designs
and Patents Act of 1988, permit copyright holders to control the import of
works.
The committee and the OFT have asked why CDs are cheaper in the US than the
UK and whether freer trade might result in lower prices for British
consumers.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, told the committee
last month that he had decided to examine CD prices in spite of the finding
by Sir Gordon Borrie, his predecessor, that there were no grounds for an MMC
inquiry. Sir Bryan told the committee: 'There is enough information there to
make me concerned about the situation.'
Music companies are resigned to a monopoly reference. They believe, however,
that they will be able to persuade the commission that parallel import
restrictions are essential to the health of UK music. They say cheap CD
imports would undermine the UK industry and deprive it of the profits
necessary for investment in new talent.
</TEXT>
