<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Telecoms group to start City service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CITY of London's streets are about to be dug up by a new
telecommunications company laying its own network. It expects to offer local
services to rival BT and Mercury by the autumn.
City of London Telecommunications (Colt) has been granted a government
licence to build and operate its own fixed-wire London network within the
M25.
It is only the second company to be granted a licence as a public
telecommunications operator since the government opened the telephone-call
market to new entrants two years ago.
Colt, an offshoot of Fidelity, a US investment management company which has
several telecoms concerns in America, intends to spend 'tens of millions' in
the next few months on the first stages of constructing its own fibre-optic
network.
It will initially concentrate on the City, with construction starting in the
Fleet Street and Bishopsgate areas.
It hopes to offer private-network services in the City by October. It also
intends to offer leased-line and other services, some in conjunction with
new line resale companies, to provide a national and international
'one-stop' facility.
Mr Paul Chisholm, Colt's managing director and a former account manager at
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, the leading US telecoms group, said he
planned to compete on price and quality.
Mr Edward Leigh, the technology minister, said that Colt would 'increase the
range of choice available to customers in the key financial and business
centre of the City of London'.
</TEXT>
