<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Snub for coal pension plea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL has signalled that it will reject a proposal from the trustees
of its staff superannuation scheme that part of a Pounds 1bn surplus should
be used to guarantee inflation-linked annual pension increases.
British Coal said that it had not yet given a formal response to the
proposals and had no timetable for doing so.
The trustees, who include representatives of both management and staff, sent
British Coal proposals in January to allocate half the surplus to scheme
members in accordance with the trust deed. Trustees said the scheme actuary
estimated that guaranteed index-linking would use up only Pounds 130m of an
estimated Pounds 1.017bn surplus as at 1992.
Pensions have been increased in line with inflation in recent years, but
future index-linking is not guaranteed. It is believed that there are
concerns about the ability to sell parts of British Coal if employers have
to provide index-linked pensions.
Guaranteeing inflation now will also leave the government with few
incentives to offer the trustees in exchange for their agreement to
surrender part of the scheme's assets. A similar plan has been proposed for
the British Rail pension scheme post-after privatisation.
Coal scheme trustees yesterday testified before the parliamentary select
committee on social security on their preferred method of running the
schemes after the disposal.
Sir Norman Siddell, chairman of the staff superannua tion scheme, said the
trustees would like to see the scheme split in two - with one pool of assets
dedicated to current and deferred pensioners, and another of assets
dedicated to those who remain employed.
The trustees said they would meet Mr Tim Eggar, the energy minister, next
week to seek assurances that there would be no worsening of benefits after
privatisation, that no future employer should be able to tap the pension
funds, and that new employers should be prohibited from transferring other
employees into the scheme.
MPs yesterday questioned the trustees about their dispute with British Coal
over the company's refusal to make a Pounds 104m payment into the scheme on
April 5.
</TEXT>
