<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Profit from sale of bank denied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SALE in May 1991 of Impexbank, the trade finance bank in Istanbul which
Mr Asil Nadir used to own, did not give him a 'single penny', Mr Nadir
claimed yesterday, John Murray Brown writes. Mr Nadir's personal creditors
say the sale was in breach of an agreement by Mr Nadir.
In 1989, the last financial year before the sale, Impexbank reported profits
of TL3.6bn and assets of TL255.6bn.
Behind the present row is a battle between Mr Nadir and Mr Bulent Semiler,
also a native of northern Cyprus and an adviser to former Turkish president
Turgut Ozal, who died last month.
Mr Semiler has said the Eliyesil family, the current owners, paid Dollars
8.9m in full for the bank which Mr Nadir bought in 1988, and that Mr Nadir
was paid Dollars 4.9m immediately. A due diligence test after the sale
established the value of the bank at Dollars 6.9m
Mr Semiler is senior director of Impexbank, and through marriage is
connected with the Eliyesil family. He was also one of the main figures
behind the rescue attempt for Polly Peck International before it was put
into administration.
Mr Nadir said yesterday: 'I don't know what the situation is now. I've not
had the time to look after anything but I intend to.' He added that he
planned to travel to Turkey soon to reclaim his business assets. He
indicated he would dispute 'vigorously and totally' that and other sales of
his Turkish assets.
</TEXT>
