FT  12 MAY 93 / World Trade News: New attack on US-EC Airbus pact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US-EC agreement over Airbus came under new attack yesterday by
Congressman Richard Gephardt, the House majority leader, who said the 1992
pact must be strengthened when it is reviewed in July, writes Nancy Dunne in
Washington.
The congressmen, a close adviser to President Bill Clinton on trade matters,
represents a Missouri district, where thousands of McDonnell Douglas jobs
are being lost to Airbus competition. The pact permits European governments
to continue providing subsidies for aircraft development.
Mr Gephardt called on the Clinton Administration to ensure that the
agreement is not adopted by other countries in the Uruguay Round.
In a speech to the Economic Strategy Institute, Mr Gephardt defended the
Administration's 'results-oriented' trade policy toward Japan. The US must
go further, investigating the practices of Japanese companies that act as
cartels in the US.
He said he would 'work day and night' to pass a North American Free Trade
Agreement if the supplemental agreements on jobs and the environment, under
negotiation, are effective. 'I don't want us to walk away from the table in
defeat,' he insisted.
See Nafta survey
