<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Spanish official lost for words in Brussels post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SUDDEN resignation of the European Commission's director general for
social affairs has cast another embarrassing spotlight on how the EC fills
its senior jobs. It also calls into question how seriously the Community
takes its vaunted ambition of building a 'social dimension' into European
integration.
Mr Sigismundo Crespo, Spanish director general of DG5 (social policy) in the
Commission, left Brussels late last week, leaving a note for his secretary
saying he would not be back. He confirmed his resignation in a subsequent
sharply worded fax from Madrid. A furious Mr Jacques Delors, Commission
president, has now summoned him back, one senior official said yesterday.
Explanations for his departure vary. Mr Crespo was said by one official to
have suffered a family tragedy. He himself is understood to have complained
that his lines of communication inside the Commission had been deliberately
blocked.
Mr Crespo took over DG5 in October. However, it was known that the social
affairs directorate had been earmarked for a Spaniard as long ago as
February 1991, because a reshuffle of top Commission jobs left Spain one
directorate general short after it had conceded transport to the UK.
With Spain and other member states unyielding over their informal quotas of
top jobs, Brussels canvassed hard to get a Spaniard of high calibre. Highly
regarded Spaniards within the Commission, like Mr Eneko Landaburu, the
Basque head of regional policy, were not interested.
Mr Crespo, best known in Spain for transferring back to the unions the
assets seized from them by Franco, was sent from Madrid and found
immediately to be out of his depth.
His main handicap was linguistic. Though a French speaker, he was unable to
communicate in English with his boss, Mr Padraig Flynn, the Irish
commissioner for social affairs. Mr Flynn has no French and had placed
British and Irish officials alongside and immediately under Mr Crespo,
hemming him in.
Senior officials in DG5 described their weekly meetings as 'like Basil
Fawlty and Manuel' in the TV comedy Fawlty Towers.
This cavalier behaviour with a department the Commission claims is vital
comes at a time when Brussels has been at cross purposes on social policy.
Mr Flynn has won support from the Twelve to prepare an EC-wide jobs
initiative. However, it emerges that Mr Delors has been working discreetly
on a similar initiative using his own network within the Commission.
</TEXT>
<XX>
