<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Government retreats in row with teachers: Patten agrees to
streamline tests from next year but union boycott will go ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT last night staged a retreat in its long-running battle with
teachers by announcing that mandatory tests in schools would be simplified
and streamlined from next year.
Its decision, rushed out in a House of Commons statement after a morning of
Downing Street crisis management, appeared to calm the rising discontent
among Tory MPs about the handling of the dispute by Mr John Patten, the
education secretary. But it failed to persuade the teachers to lift their
boycott on this summer's tests.
Mr Patten told MPs that in 1994 the tests for seven and 14-year-olds would
be restricted to the 'core' subjects of English, mathematics and science
(and in Wales, the Welsh language). The government will decide later whether
to add technology for 14-year-olds.
The row, which had set the government against most of the educational
establishment and prompted growing unease among parents, contributed to the
government's disastrous performance in last week's county council elections.
Earlier Mr Patten was said to have been 'incandescent' at press reports that
the prime minister's office had 'bounced' him into a climbdown.
A Downing Street official denied he had been the source of the reports. But
senior ministers confirmed that Mr Patten had been under intense pressure
from Mr John Major and cabinet colleagues to produce a formula to defuse the
row. Some colleagues believe Mr Patten remains vulnerable in the expected
July cabinet reshuffle, but yesterday, at least, Mr Major offered his public
backing.
From 1994 the content of the tests will be simplified and the government
will consider easing the burden on teachers by using outside examiners to
mark them.
The number of subjects for which teachers have to compile assessments of
classroom work will also be cut. Mr Patten, saying next year's tests would
'focus on the basics', delayed until 1995 the nationwide introduction of
testing of 11-year-olds.
But he refused to bow to teachers' demands that the far more complicated
tests due this year be scrapped. That left the teaching unions welcoming the
planned 1994 changes but refusing to lift this summer's boycott.
The unions, whose case has won unprecedented backing across all sections of
the teaching profession, are unwilling to conduct the tests before the
outcome of the full-scale review of the national curriculum by Sir Ron
Dearing.
By contrast, Mr Patten said this year's tests were essential to inform Sir
Ron's review. He appealed to the unions to respond by ending their boycott.
Privately, ministers were admitting the government's position owed much more
to Mr Patten's determination to avoid capitulating to the unions than to any
real hope the tests will go ahead. Mr Eamonn O'Kane, National Association of
Schoolmasters Union of Women Teachers' deputy general secretary, said: 'What
he's proposed for 1994 doesn't go the whole way but certainly tries to open
up the issues we would want addressed.' But he criticised the decision to
press on with tests this year as a 'completely illogical and pointless
exercise'.
The government was further embarrassed last night by a revolt of five Tory
MPs over its plans to restrict fishermen's time at sea and by defeats in the
House of Lords on rights of leaseholders to buyfreeholds.
Student loans repayment shift offers Pounds 4bn bonus Page 9
Tests set to plague government Page 10
</TEXT>
