<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / 2,200 jobs threatened at Swan Hunter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of the long-established shipbuilding industry on Tyneside was
placed in jeopardy yesterday when Swan Hunter lost its bid for a vital
contract to build a 20,000-tonne helicopter carrier for the navy.
Swan Hunter described the surprise decision as 'potentially terminal'.
Labour MPs said it would force the closure of Swan Hunter and put 6,000
people in the north-east out of work.
The contract, believed to be worth about Pounds 170m, has gone instead to
VSEL, the submarine yard at Barrow-in-Furness, Cumbria, in conjunction with
the Norwegian-owned Scottish company Kvaerner Govan.
Mr Jonathan Aitken, defence procurement minister, said the VSEL bid won 'by
a very substantial margin of more than Pounds 50m'. Neither VSEL nor Swan
Hunter would comment on details of the respective bids.
Mr Aitken said the government had taken 'full account' of wider factors such
as Swan Hunter's future. But he added: 'The final judgment was made on our
normal technical and value-for-money criteria.'
The plan for a helicopter carrier was thought likely to be dropped in MoD
budget cuts but was revived in March. The ship, to be called HMS Ocean, is
designed to carry 12 helicopters, capable of landing several hundred Royal
Marines.
Swan Hunter was hoping to secure subsequent contracts for two large assault
ships, worth about Pounds 200m each. Work on current orders - completing
three navy frigates - will run out by the end of next year.
Swan Hunter's yard at Wallsend employs 2,200, compared with 4,500 when it
was privatised in a management buyout in 1986. The company is owned by 36
senior managers; it has no parent to fall back on.
Since it opened in the 1870s, it has constructed 2,700 ships, from the
famous Cunard liner Mauretania to the current aircraft carriers Ark Royal
and Illustrious.
Yesterday, with a terseness which underlined the seriousness of its
predicament, the management refused any comment beyond a brief statement
from joint chief executive Dr Roger Vaughan. It said: 'The order being
awarded to anyone other than Swan Hunter will have serious consequences.'
VSEL said the jobs argument was the same whether the contract went to
Barrow-in-Furness or the Tyne. The deal marks the submarine builder's return
to surface ship work after an 11-year absence. Under the contract, the ship
itself will be built at Kvaerner Govan on Clydeside and will be turned into
a military vessel at VSEL.
The work will sustain about 500 jobs at VSEL over the next 18 months. The
yard, which has cut its workforce to 7,700 from 14,300 in 1989, is still
expected to make further reductions.
