<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / Nadir pledges to fight disposal of Polly Peck assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KYRENIA, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR ASIL NADIR, the fugitive businessman, said from his refuge in northern
Cyprus yesterday that he planned to move back into the com-pany's
headquarters on the island in the next few days and fight attempts in Turkey
to dispose of the assets of his former company, Polly Peck International.
Mr Nadir, who jumped Pounds 3.5m bail last week, said in an interview with
the Financial Times that he would go to Turkey very soon to pursue
'vigorously and totally' the assets of both Polly Peck and his personal
businesses.
'I do intend to challenge the sales of Polly Peck assets everywhere,' he
said.
Mr Nadir, who fled to northern Cyprus from Britain last week, claimed he had
a plan to recover the assets of Polly Peck and recompense the shareholders,
who, he said, 'have not got a chance at all in the hands of the
administrators'.
Asked what he would do about those who had to surrender the bail put up for
him in the UK, Mr Nadir said his 'supporters will be able to handle any
situation and nobody will be hardshipped'.
Dressed in a linen jacket and smoking constantly, Mr Nadir spoke in the
vaulted drawing room of his family house in Lapta. He played down the
urgency of his next moves. 'I will first visit my father's grave,' he said
while being served coffee on a Japanese lacquer table by a waiter in a
maroon waistcoat.
Mr Nadir's fightback plan was confirmed in London yesterday when it emerged
that he had begun to reclaim his personal assets in Turkey from the hands of
his UK court-appointed trustee.
Mr Nadir has successfully applied to the Turkish courts in the last two days
to revoke the power of attorney granted to his trustee in bankruptcy. This
has blocked action by the trustee to appoint new directors and take control
of AN Graphics, a printing company with assets worth several million pounds.
Turkish and Cypriot businesses of Polly Peck contributed about two-thirds of
the group's Pounds 161m pre-tax profit in 1989, the last full year before it
was forced into administration.
Mr Ismet Sezgin, Turkish interior minister, said last week that Mr Nadir
would be free to travel to Turkey.
Mr Neil Cooper, a partner at accountants Robson Rhodes, who is the trustee
in bankruptcy, confirmed that he was seeking legal advice on ways to fight
Mr Nadir's action.
'I feel disappointed because we were making some progress in the recovery of
assets,' he said. 'This goes against what Mr Nadir implied in his statements
(when he said) that he would be helping his shareholders.'
Although replaced by the administrators as director of the Turkish
companies, Mr Nadir is still director of the Cypriot companies, Sunzest, the
fruit export business, the Unipac packaging company in the Famagusta
freeport and three hotels.
Life through the eyes of Asil Nadir
FT interview: Page 8
</TEXT>
