<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last week in the major New York auctions the late Andy Warhol's art was
quite out of favour - which gives added poignancy to the Late Show Special
The War Over Warhol. This delves into the controversy over the Warhol
Foundation, which was intended to immortalise the artist and his works, and
to do good, too. As usual there are disputes over Warhol's will, the
Trustees, over everything, and so far the only beneficiaries are the
lawyers. (BBC 2 at 11.15).
Forty Minutes (BBC 2 at 9.50) has a knack of spotting off-beat stories. In
'Three Big Men' it follows the fortunes of the three strong British sumo
wrestling team in Japan. At the national trials in London there were just
three entrants so the team really picked itself. Their experiences among the
big men in Tokyo makes rivetting viewing.
The controversial Camille Paglia, the scourge of the feminists, is let loose
on the Lolita syndrome in Without Walls (9 pm on Channel 4). Also in the
usual double bill is Paul Eddy, a Provencal resident, who gives a very
different view of his adopted village to that propagated by neighbour Peter
Mayle.
</TEXT>
