<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Charging road users has high
political cost - Toll roads unleashed explosive anger among the Norwegians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSPORT secretary Mr John MacGregor yesterday came face to face with some
of the political risks and realities of introducing a system of charging
people for the use of London's roads.
On a fact-finding visit to one of the world's few road pricing schemes in
the Norwegian capital of Oslo, he learned that shoppers, the young and the
low-paid had emerged as some of the hardest hit by the charges. When the
system was introduced in 1990, there were attempts to blow up the toll
booths. It has remained unpopular, with the number of Oslo inhabitants
opposed to the scheme little lower now than the level of 60 per cent
initially.
However, Mr MacGregor was told that the proceeds from the tolls had
succeeded in financing the construction of new roads in the city, mostly in
tunnels, which had helped eased city centre congestion.
Mr MacGregor is visiting Scandinavia to see what lessons can be learned for
his own plans to introduce road charging to Britain, initially on trunk
roads and motorways and later in urban areas.
He intends to set out his plans for motorway charges in a green paper in the
next four to six weeks, but yesterday he said he would not take any
decisions on urban road charging until a Department of Transport study of
the issue had been completed towards the end of 1994.
The Oslo urban road charging system was introduced in February 1990 with
cross-party support to help finance a NK12bn (Pounds 1.138bn) programme of
urban road building and improvements to public transport. The city is now
ringed with 19 toll plazas where drivers pay an entry fee, either manually
in cash or electronically through a debiting system similar to the one
operating on London's Dartford Crossing.
The entry fee is NK11 for vehicles up to 3.5 tonnes and double that for
lorries, with discounts available for season tickets or multiple-entry
tickets. Only motorcycles, buses, cars being driven by the handicapped,
emergency vehicles and funeral processions are exempt from the charge.
When vehicles go through the electronic debiting lanes without a payment
being successfully deducted, their registration numbers are photographed so
that they can be traced.
Mr MacGregor was told that the violation rate was only 0.1 per cent, but
some drivers went to elaborate lengths to avoid being charged - for example,
covering their number plates with mud, bending the plates over so that they
were horizontal to the road, or driving on the tail of the vehicle in front
so that the camera could not get a clear view.
Officials from Norway's Public Roads Administration said the introduction of
road charges was estimated to have left total car journeys into the capital
5 per cent lower than they would otherwise have been.
However, a high proportion of better-off workers had received help with the
cost of an annual season ticket from their employers, while those who had
stopped making journeys were mainly the less well-off and among off-peak
users such as shoppers. The charges had also failed to produce any
detectable increase in the use of public transport.
Mr Olav Softeland, director general of the public roads administration, said
it was 'basically an unpopular thing' to start charging for roads that had
previously been free, and a 'hazardous thing' for a politician to put his
name to.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
</CN>
