<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Backbench revolt looms over VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS WERE last night trying to curb the extent of an embarrassing
revolt over the government's plans to extend value added tax to domestic
fuel, as the Finance Bill implementing the Budget began its Commons
committee stage.
Mr Michael Portillo, chief Treasury secretary, was forced to run a gauntlet
of backbench dissent in the wake of last week's morale-sapping election
results for the government.
Mr William Powell, the Tory MP for Corby, was the first backbencher to
pledge open defiance after a string of worried and sceptical Conservative
interventions during Mr Portillo's speech.
A common thread in their misgivings was the impact of the government's plans
on those with pensions and savings marginally above the level entitling them
to support from the social security system. Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, announced in the Budget that he planned to extend VAT to
domestic fuel from next April.
In a measured but determined tone, Mr Powell said he would vote against the
government 'with enthusiasm', adding: 'I know my constituents would feel
ashamed of me if I were to vote for it tonight.'
He accused Mr Lamont of making a 'very serious error of judgment' in
extending VAT into an area never previously contemplated by the Commons.
He said it was this extension of VAT that had encouraged traditional
Conservative voters in Northamptonshire to stay at home in last week's
county council elections.
Mrs Angela Browning, the Tory MP for Tiverton, expressed similar sentiments
and said that voters in the south-west were already having to find the money
to pay sharply increased water charges.
Mr Terry Dicks, Tory MP for Hayes and Harlington, attacked the government
for 'punishing pensioners' while subsidising the arts and contributing
significant sums to overseas aid.
Mr Portillo took pains to emphasise both the urgency of the need to tackle
the public sector borrowing requirement and the full extent of the benefits
which pensioners and those on income support had derived from other
government policies.
'It may be that the increases the government has made in help to the poorest
people have been so numerous and so large that the House is out of touch
with where we have now reached,' he said.
Details of the measures the government proposed to help those worst-hit by
the VAT extension would be set out in the autumn uprating statement.
But he said it would be 'unrealistic to give extra help to all pensioners
over and above the retail prices index effect', because 'we could be talking
about another Pounds 1bn on benefit'.
For Labour, Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief Treasury secretary, urged Tory
backbenchers to join the opposition in voting against the government, saying
it was the backbenchers' chance to show that 'even if the government cannot
listen' to the electorate 'perhaps they can'.
She said the government's proposals would make 'some of the poorest and most
vulnerable pay the price for the government's economic incompetence'.
She added: 'This VAT ex-tension paves the way for further VAT extensions to
children's clothes, newspapers and food.'
</TEXT>
