<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Pressure on Nadir as bank shuts HQ
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN, GILLIAN TETT and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KYRENIA,, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE POSITION of Mr Asil Nadir, the fugitive Turkish-Cypriot businessman,
appeared to be weakening yesterday. Britain stepped up its diplomatic
pressure on northern Cyprus and Mr Nadir's privately owned bank announced
that it was closing its headquarters - the first indication of serious
trouble in his financial empire on the island.
In the strongest warning to northern Cyprus from the UK government so far,
Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, Foreign Office minister, yesterday warned that
sanctions had not been ruled out and that northern Cyprus's interests could
be badly damaged if it failed to return Mr Nadir to England.
Mr Garel-Jones said: 'The Turkish Cypriots should appreciate the damage it
could do to their interests if they were to acquire a reputation as a refuge
for fugitives.'
He added that if Mr Nadir travelled to Turkey then Turkey's reputation could
suffer similarly.
Mr Rauf Denktash, the Turkish Cypriot leader, yesterday said that he had no
intention of returning Mr Nadir to Britain. Instead he urged the British
authorities to prosecute Mr Nadir in northern Cyprus.
In the first indication that Mr Nadir's troubles are affecting his private
businesses on the island, Kibris Endustri Bankasi, Mr Asil Nadir's privately
owned bank in northern Cyprus, is planning to close its Nicosia
headquarters. It told its landlords at the end of April that it intended to
vacate the premises. It has reportedly had problems meeting its rent
payments.
The northern Cyprus government has already put a general lien on all the
assets relating to Mr Nadir. This follows the failure to pay social security
and other official dues of 35bn Turkish lira (Pounds 2.28m) and TL40bn,
related to his personal debts to the government.
It is possible for Mr Nadir to be prosecuted in northern Cyprus because,
according to a provision in the criminal law of northern Cyprus, a citizen
can be tried and convicted in the local courts for a crime committed outside
the territory.
The UK's Serious Fraud Office has refrained from initiating such action
because the territory is not formally recognised by the UK.
Such a move would require the SFO to provide the information to proceed.
Meanwhile, BDO Binder Hamlyn, the accountancy firm, last night clarified the
work it had conducted on behalf of Mr Nadir in northern Cyprus.
Mr Nadir said on Friday that the firm had shown that monies allegedly stolen
by him were accounted for in the books of Unipac, the packaging company
based in northern Cyprus.
Mr Adrian Burn, managing partner in London, stressed that his firm had been
commissioned by Mr Nadir's former solicitors in 1991 to conduct a limited
review which reconciled bank statements with book entries for certain
specific transactions. He said: 'We were not asked, and did not form an
opinion on the whole picture. The transactions were consistent with the bank
statements and cash entries.'
</TEXT>
