<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Revenue quizzed BBC over Birt 4 years ago
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC was challenged more than four years ago by the Inland Revenue over
the employment status of Mr John Birt, its director-general.
The Revenue, which has for years been tightening the rules for freelances
who work entirely or predominantly for one employer, wrote to the
corporation questioning Mr Birt's arrangement less than two years after he
became deputy director-general.
The BBC decided at the time to defend the practice. It is believed that the
BBC's tax advisers, Coopers &amp; Lybrand, were used to rebut the Inland Revenue
approach, which was not renewed.
It is unclear whether Mr Marmaduke Hussey, chairman of the BBC, knew about
the Inland Revenue's approach, although he is ultimately responsible for the
remuneration of both the director-general and the deputy director-general.
A row erupted at the end of February when it was revealed that Mr Birt had
not joined the corporation's staff. Instead he was hired as a freelance
consultant, initially as deputy director-general, and was paid through his
private company, John Birt Productions. He finally joined the BBC staff last
week.
Mr Birt has also received contributions to his private pension from the BBC
in addition to his basic pay. These payments have never been disclosed.
The pension contributions were paid to John Birt Productions, a company
owned by Mr Birt and his wife Jane - this means that Mr Birt was paid more
than had been thought. The actual total is difficult to discern because in
addition to basic pay and pension money, Mr Birt's BBC expenses were also
paid through the private company.
In 1991, the last year for which accounts are available, the company's
'administration expenses' were Pounds 159,174. In that year there was a
payment of Pounds 36,167 to the company pension plans.
In January Mr Birt agreed a Pounds 200,000 pay package and the corporation
has confirmed that he had formally joined the staff and would be eligible to
join the BBC pension scheme.
It is not clear whether the private pension payments will continue on top of
the Pounds 200,000 package.
BBC executives who know Mr Birt believe that the additional payments for his
private pension are likely to continue in addition to his pay package.
</TEXT>
