<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Iraq arms papers still withheld
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KEY GOVERNMENT documents which could shed light on the extent to which
ministers sidestepped government guidelines on defence sales to Iraq are
still being withheld from the arms-for-Iraq inquiry it emerged yesterday.
The missing documents include details of a secret system for classifying
countries according to their perceived security risk, which was apparently
used by the Ministry of Defence in processing exports to Iraq.
Guidelines announced to parliament in October 1985 officially made defence
sales more restrictive both to Iraq and Iran. But it is thought the internal
classification system for Iraq remained unchanged from 1981 until August
1990, when Kuwait was invaded.
Reference to a classification system code-named Table X was made by a former
senior official of the Ministry of Defence, Mr Christopher Sandars, in
evidence at the start of the second week of the Scott inquiry's public
hearings.
Mr Sandars said that under an internal system set up in the ministry in the
1980s, British defence companies wishing to trade with Iraq dealt directly
with defence officials, some of whom were charged with promoting exports.
The inquiry heard that the opinions of these officials, in consultation with
the Foreign Office, were often 'fairly definitive' in deciding whether a
company was granted an export licence. The system of 'informal clearances'
brokered by an internal arms working group did not involve the Department of
Trade and Industry.
Mr Sandars was told by Lord Justice Scott that he would be required to
attend a fresh hearing after he had provided missing documents covering
Table X and other important areas of defence policy.
Mr Sandars was head of the MoD's Secretariat 13 in charge of defence sales
between September 1980 and December 1984. He subsequently served as
assistant secretary of state (Defence Export Services Administration), a
separate department which also oversaw defence sales.
It emerged last night that Mr Sandars remains a serving senior civil
servant. He was recently moved to the Cabinet Office's Defence and Overseas
Affairs Secretariat which co-ordinates policy between departments.
Sources close to the inquiry were playing down suggestions of a clash over
missing documents between Lord Justice Scott and the government although
they said the judge was determined to get all the documents he had asked for
before preparing his report later in the year.
The hearing continues today.
</TEXT>
