<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Channel tunnel may face delay
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSMANCHE LINK, the consortium building the Channel tunnel, said yesterday
that the opening of the tunnel could be delayed until 1995.
Mr Philippe Montagner, TML vice-president, told shareholders that
construction of the tunnel was not nearly finished, in spite of what
Eurotunnel, the tunnel operator said.
He said that more than a year was needed to make software and to carry out
tests.
'The installations as such are on the verge of being finished but that is
not the case for software or tests, and in the best of cases over another
year of work is still needed today,' Mr Montagner said.
He said talks between Eurotunnel and TML were blocked and there was no
agreement on costs, the opening date or financing.
TML was ready to negotiate if Eurotunnel made an offer that could serve as a
basis of negotiation, he said, adding that a 1995 opening would only be
possible if 'perfect co-operation' between all parties in the project was
reached.
TML favoured a phased opening even if this was not planned in the initial
contract, he said.
Eurotunnel said it was sticking by a recent statement that, if it ccould
count on the co-operation of its contractors, the tunnel should be ready to
open in 1994.
