<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Uncertainty grows over Independent ownership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNCERTAINTY grew last night over the future ownership of Newspaper
Publishing, publishers of The Independent and Independent on Sunday,
following the failed attempt to buy the Observer, Raymond Snoddy writes.
The company declined to comment on reports that the two principal
shareholders, El Pais of Spain and La Repubblica of Italy had let it be
known formally they each wanted to increase its stake from 18 per cent to 25
per cent.
Both companies bought part of their holding at Pounds 5 a share but the
latest package of shares went at Pounds 1.90 a share to Cerruti, the Italian
manufacturer of printing presses.
If El Pais and La Repubblica end up jointly owning a majority stake this
would call into question the position of the founder of The Independent, Mr
Andreas Whittam Smith, as both chief executive of the company and editor.
Last week Sir Ralf Dahrendorf resigned as chairman of Newspaper Publishing
partly because of opposition to the plan to buy the Observer but also
because of what he saw as Mr Whittam Smith's increasingly authoritarian
style of management. The company is urgently seeking a new chairman and Mr
Ian Hay Davison, already a non-executive director, is seen as favourite.
In the six months to March Newspaper Publishing had pre-tax profits of
Pounds 341,000 but the company is likely to face increasing competition once
The Guardian completes its expected purchase of the Observer.
As a result of the last re-financing, limits on the size of individual
shareholdings were removed. This means that Newspaper Publishing is now open
to takeover should it run into financial difficulties and need to raise more
capital.
