<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Professionals who want manufacturing taken seriously:
Proposals to improve the image and status of engineers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE board of a much-criticised Pounds 100m business will meet today to hear
how a new relationship between head office and 42 diverse affiliates -
leading ultimately, perhaps, to a full-blown merger - could sharpen its
image and improve its products.
Another troubled British manufacturing company looking for a fresh start? Up
to a point, yes. The business is the UK professional engineering structure,
the 'board' is the Engineering Council, and the affiliates are the 42
professional institutions, big and small.
Collectively, the institutions and the council have a turnover of Pounds
100m, and their most important product is their engineers.
But the affiliates are not happy. Mr Terry Harrison, chief executive of
Rolls-Royce and a council member, said: 'Why is manufacturing industry so
undervalued in this country? It is more than a coincidence that the
engineering profession is also under-rated and undervalued by the government
and by the general public. The engineer is seen as the guy who has come to
mend the gas cooker.'
Mr Harrison and other industrialists on the council, including Sir Colin
Chandler, chief executive of Vickers, and Sir Anthony Gill, chairman of
Lucas Industries, are due to attend today's meeting.
The professions and the council, which acts as an umbrella body, have a key
role in attracting young people into engineering, developing the skills of
professional engineers, and setting standards.
A key to that is to raise the status of engineers among the general public,
the City, and the government.
Companies that employ engineers are watching the negotiations. Mr Neil
Johnson, director-general of the Engineering Employers Federation, said:
'The long-term success of the engineering industry and the profession are
interdependent.'
At today's meeting Sir John Fairclough, chairman of the council, will
outline proposals from a steering group for a 'new relationship' of
co-operation between the council and the institutions.
This could lead to the creation of a single body in which the institutions
are grouped into six divisions. The meeting foreshadows the start of a
nationwide exercise designed to stimulate debate of the reform proposals,
which were creating controversy even before the ink was dry.
Sir John sees two important industrial dimensions to the plans. The first is
the importance of a strong single body for setting standards of knowledge
and skills on which industry can depend.
The second is to develop engineering as a platform for a career in
management. 'We need to create an environment where engineers are more able
to reach the boardroom than under the present arrangements,' he said. 'There
are too many accountants in the boardroom, but that is the fault of the
engineering profession.'
Achieving this would require a more flexible system, producing engineers
with more 'interdisciplinary' abilities than are produced by the present
system, where each institution retains its right to accredit courses. 'All
industrialists are asking for this,' Sir John said.
The four big institutions have already said they believe the case for a
single body has not yet been made, and Sir John admits it will not be
possible to decide on that until the new relationship has been established.
But industry has welcomed the proposals in full.
Sir Colin, who chairs the council's standing committee on industry, said
issues such as standard-setting and developing engineering in the education
system were much better handled by a single body.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8711 Engineering Services.
    P8611 Business Associations.
</IN>
<XX>
