<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Auditors told to be tougher on accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUDITORS' reports in the annual accounts of companies will be fundamentally
changed under guidelines announced yesterday by the Auditing Practices
Board.
Auditors will be required to take a firmer line in assessing whether the
accounts presented by the directors are a 'true and fair view' of a
company's financial position.
The audit statement will also be substantially expanded to include details
of the nature of the work carried out by the auditors and the
responsibilities of both them and the directors of the company.
Mr Nigel Macdonald, president of the Institute of Chartered Accountants of
Scotland and chairman of the board's working party, said: 'This requires a
fundamental change recognising for the first time that not all readers of
accounts have a proper understanding of the respective responsibilities of
auditors and directors.'
Auditors will no longer have the option of expressing opinions that say the
accounts are true and fair 'subject to' the effects of financial
uncertainties such as outstanding litigation or contracts subject to
dispute.
Instead, they will be forced to qualify the accounts - rejecting the view
that they agree with the figures - unless they are satisfied with the
estimates and disclosures given by directors of these uncertainties.
In either case, they will be expected to provide details of any 'fundamental
uncertainty' with a description and details of potential risks and costs.
Mr Macdonald said: 'The standard has been honoured slightly differently in
the past than it will be in the future. We're trying to abolish auditors
sitting on the fence.'
Auditors will still have the option of issuing reports which are qualified,
unqualified, which disclaim opinion or present an adverse opinion.
The new report is still likely to be written to a standard form of words,
but will stress that the preparation of the accounts is the responsibility
of directors and the auditors form an independent opinion based on their
audit.
It says the audit is conducted in accordance with auditing standards, based
on a test examination of evidence relevant to the disclosures in the
accounts and the judgments of the directors.
This wording reflects a recommendation in the report of the Cadbury
committee on the financial aspects of corporate governance, which was
published last December.
The new requirements closely reflect a consultation draft issued by the
board in May last year, and will become mandatory for companies with
financial year-ends after September 30. The board is urging voluntary
compliance before this date.
Auditors' report on financial statements. Auditing Practices Board.
Accountancy Books, PO Box 6SO, Central Milton Keynes, MK9 2JX. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
