<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Profit at BNF hit by Thorp delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH NUCLEAR Fuels' annual profits have fallen by at least Pounds 60m,
partly because of the delay in starting its controversial Thorp nuclear
reprocessing plant, the company's newsletter reports.
The pre-tax profit for the year to March 1993, which BNF expects to be less
than Pounds 100m when finalised, has also been hit by the unplanned shutdown
of the facilities for handling fuel from Magnox power stations for 48 days
last year.
Mr Neville Chamberlain, BNF chief executive, warned that the delay in
starting Thorp, which BNF says is costing Pounds 2m a week, would also hit
the current year's earnings.
BNF had expected that Thorp, which has taken Pounds 2.8bn and nearly 10
years to build, would get an operating licence from the Department of the
Environment in January. The complexity of the decision, and a public
consultation which yielded 80,000 reponses, have led to delay, however.
The department's lawyers have warned that the government may need to
consider the economic case as well as the environmental and health factors,
even though a more full evaluation could delay a decision further. BNF
argues that no further assessment beyond the pollution inspectorate's report
is necessary.
Mr Chamberlain said recent leaks at Sellafield had no 'radiological
significance' and posed no health risks, but added: 'We have a lot to do in
educating the media, politicians and the public to help them understand
these concepts.'
</TEXT>
