<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / Ciampi set to clear second hurdle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Italian government of Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi looked set yesterday for a
comfortable victory in a vote of confidence in the senate, the upper house
of parliament, which is scheduled for later this week, writes Haig Simonian.
The debate marked his second parliamentary test within a week after last
Friday's successful vote of confidence in the chamber of deputies. It
coincided with a sharp rise in the value of the lira, reflecting increasing
support for the new government.
The currency was quoted at L916.88 against the D-Mark, its highest level
since early January. It started gathering strength last week as dealers
regained confidence in Mr Ciampi's government after a shaky start when four
cabinet ministers resigned within hours of taking office.
The upturn came as Mr Antonio Fazio, Mr Ciampi's successor as governor of
the Bank of Italy, told fellow central bankers in Basle that a recovery in
the Italian economy could not come through lower interest rates alone.
