FT  11 MAY 93 / Twelve give blessing to plan for east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC foreign ministers yesterday gave a broadly warm welcome to European
Commission proposals to accelerate the political and economic integration of
six former communist east European countries into the European Community.
France called for a study on how the Commission's bolder-than-expected plan
to liberalise trade with eastern Europe will affect EC member states, and
others said they needed more information before tendering their support.
Britain, Denmark and Germany signalled strong backing, with the UK
indicating it would like to see even more efforts to dismantle trade
barriers. Denmark, which holds the EC presidency, wants to make trade
liberalisation with eastern Europe a centrepiece of the EC summit in
Copenhagen next month.
