<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 93 / UK comes close to wide-screen TV pact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN yesterday came closer than ever to agreeing a European strategy for
developing advanced cinema-quality television, but blocked a deal after a
funding dispute.
EC ministers will discuss the issue again on June 16. Failure to agree then
could kill the Commission's seven-year-old ambition to back European
advanced television against US and Japanese competition.
Over the past 18 months, Britain has argued for changes in Commission plans
to kick-start the EC market for wide-screen television, and constantly
sought justification for proposed spending. It agreed yesterday that a
Danish compromise met many objections.
Brussels will thus start work on amending earlier legislation in line with
the proposed new strategy. It will also begin examining how to develop
European digital high-definition television, the technology Britain believes
will supersede EC-backed standards.
Mr Edward Leigh, British industry minister, indicated earlier that the UK
would oppose any funding plan which cost the EC more than Ecu150m (Pounds
118m) between now and the end of 1996. The other countries said they could
only agree to Ecu285m, against the Ecu850m first proposed by Brussels last
year. All but the Netherlands said they could even accept an Ecu226m plan.
Under the plan backed by 11 member states, the Community would put up
Ecu200m to develop programmes in the new wide-screen format, conditional on
equal industry funding. A further Ecu85m (to be boosted by Ecu21m of
industry funding) would be held in reserve for projects submitted later by
countries with less developed audiovisual sectors.
</TEXT>
